{
  "query": "What are the effects on butterfly and moth communities of opening up forest canopies through clearing, coppicing, or thinning?",
  "relevant_summary": "Across studies, opening forest canopies through clearing, coppicing, or thinning commonly increased butterfly richness and/or abundance, while moth richness and/or abundance often declined relative to closed or mature forest. Clearing or opening patches: cleared patches had greater butterfly species richness but lower moth species richness than unmanaged, coppiced, or closed-canopy forest; large cleared patches supported higher butterfly richness and abundance than undisturbed forest; macro-moth abundance was lower on wider rides, and macro-moth richness on rides was similar to mature forest; butterfly abundance often increased (including chequered blue, woodland brown, high brown fritillary, small pearl-bordered fritillary), with some declines over the first three years; heath fritillary abundance was higher 2\u20134 years after clearance than in older or first-year patches; a translocated baton blue population increased and survived at least two years; some species used cleared areas more and breeding sites increased; a European review reported small patch clearing benefited 19/67 butterfly species of conservation concern (3938). Coppicing: different-aged coppice supported different communities and more unique macro-moth species than mature forest; butterfly richness was higher than in unmanaged woodland, while macro-moth richness and abundance were lower than in mature forest; butterfly abundance (including heath fritillary) was higher in woodland coppiced 2\u201315 years prior than in >15-year coppice; some species increased after coppicing alongside other measures, and pearl\u2011bordered fritillaries persisted longer in coppiced or young plantation woodland; released pearl\u2011bordered fritillaries bred at least once (3939). Thinning: one to four years after thinning (often with prescribed burning, mulching, or nearby felling), butterfly richness and abundance increased compared to unmanaged or pre-treatment conditions; partially cleared plots had higher butterfly but lower moth species richness than closed-canopy forest; in a tropical forest, overall fruit\u2011feeding butterfly richness, diversity, and abundance were similar to unmanaged forest, but rarer species were less frequently caught (3940).",
  "action_ids": [
    "3938",
    "3939",
    "3940"
  ]
}

