{
  "query": "How does rotational burning compare to leaving unburned patches during prescribed fires for butterfly populations in US prairies?",
  "relevant_summary": "In US prairies and oak savannas, leaving unburned patches during prescribed burning was associated with increased Karner blue butterfly abundance over 2\u20133 years and use of all surveyed unburned patches, and with six of nine specialist species being more abundant (one less abundant, two similar) at sites with unburned areas than at sites without them [3879]. Under rotational burning, multiple US studies reported mixed outcomes: total butterfly or grassland-specialist abundance was typically higher on prairies burned more than 1\u20134 years earlier than on recently burned areas, with some species (e.g., regal fritillary) peaking several years post-burn, while others (e.g., Karner blue) showed similar abundance in rotationally burned and unmanaged sites; species richness and community responses varied by site and management combinations (e.g., rotational burning alone vs. with grazing) [3883].",
