{
  "query": "What does the evidence say about the long-term success of re-establishing butterfly populations through translocation or captive-release?",
  "relevant_summary": "Across studies of butterfly and moth re-establishments, a review across the UK and Ireland found that 25% of translocated and captive-released butterfly populations survived at least three years, 38% died out within three years, and only 8% were known to survive for more than 10 years (action 3909; action 3914). Multiple case studies reported translocated populations persisting and increasing for 2\u201312 years, with some persisting 1\u201349 years, while others died out within 0\u20137 years (action 3909). A review reported large copper populations persisted up to 38 years but ultimately died out or required supplementation (action 3909). For captive-bred releases, populations in several cases persisted 2\u201328 years and increased, but some died out after 1\u201312 years or required further releases; in one replicated case, 3 of 10 barberry carpet moth releases established with at least one persisting five years (action 3914). Comparative evidence indicates released captive-bred large copper caterpillars had lower survival than captive, wild, or translocated caterpillars (action 3914), while one site comparison found translocated large copper caterpillars survived better than released captive-bred caterpillars (action 3909). Overall, evidence documents both successes and failures over multi-year timescales, with relatively few documented cases persisting beyond a decade without supplementation (action 3909; action 3914).",
  "action_ids": [
    "3909",
    "3914"
  ]
}

