  "relevant_summary": "Protecting greenfield or undeveloped land in urban areas was associated with higher butterfly species richness than urban parks or non-native plantations in site comparisons from Singapore and Mexico [3836]. Altering mowing regimes on urban greenspaces and road verges showed: higher species richness and diversity on less frequently mown or unmown greenspaces in Germany and the UK; no effect on species richness along some Canadian verges; higher abundance on unmown public parks in the UK and on some unmown verges/under power lines in Canada; higher ringlet abundance on Finnish roadsides mown in late summer than mid-summer; fewer traffic-killed butterflies on Polish verges mown less frequently or later; greater occupancy by scarce copper on less frequently mown Swedish urban grasslands; and butterfly presence on Dutch verges mown once or twice a year or not mown, with presence on mowed verges only where hay was removed [3841]. Stopping the use of insecticides and herbicides in gardens was associated with higher butterfly abundance, while not using fungicides and snail pellets was associated with lower butterfly abundance, in a replicated site comparison in France [3900]. No studies were found evaluating the effects of planting trees to reduce urban temperatures on butterflies and moths [3838].",
