{
  "query": "How do different methods of creating field margins in European farmland, such as uncultivated strips versus sown wildflower strips, compare in their effectiveness for butterfly communities?",
  "relevant_summary": "Across multiple studies, sown wildflower or floristically enhanced margins generally supported higher butterfly species richness and abundance than uncultivated or grass-only margins. Field margins sown with wildflowers had greater butterfly richness and abundance than grass-only field margins in studies from the UK and Sweden, and more than conventional/unsown margins or cropped fields in several European studies [3932]. Floristically enhanced grass buffers or wildflower strips also showed higher butterfly richness and abundance than standard grass margins or uncultivated margins in UK and Swedish studies [3982]. In contrast, uncultivated margins often had lower butterfly richness and abundance than margins sown with grasses/forbs or wildflowers, though outcomes improved when margins were wider/longer, left uncut or only cut outside summer, and located near existing grassland; some studies reported similar or higher values under specific conditions [3981]. A Swedish comparison within grass margins found those sown with legumes or clover ley had higher butterfly richness and abundance than uncultivated margins [3982]. Overall, evidence indicates sown wildflower strips and floristically enhanced margins outperform uncultivated strips for butterfly community richness and abundance in the available studies [3932, 3982, 3981].",
  "action_ids": [
