{
  "query": "What are the observed effects of ceasing grassland management, either by stopping mowing or grazing, on butterfly abundance and diversity?",
  "relevant_summary": "Across studies, ceasing mowing or grazing often resulted in butterfly and moth communities similar to managed grasslands, but in one study the community shifted over six years to being dominated by generalist species with fewer generations per year [3957, 3956]. Species richness frequently remained similar to managed sites after 3\u201320 years or an unspecified period, though some studies reported lower richness after >50 years or 6\u201313 years without mowing, and lower richness after >5\u201320 years or many years without grazing; in contrast, richness was higher in meadows not cut all summer, in grasslands abandoned 4\u201310 years versus extensively/commercially grazed, and where grazing had ceased 2\u20139 years compared to >10 years or currently grazed [3957, 3956]. Abundance responses were mixed: several studies recorded lower abundance after >1\u201320 years without mowing or grazing, while other studies found higher abundance after >3 years, temporary abandonment, or when uncut all summer; some studies reported similar abundance to grazed/mown sites, and species-specific outcomes varied [3957, 3956]. In some cases, woodland and hedgerow butterflies and burnet moths were more abundant after 1\u20136 years of abandonment, whereas grassland or farmland species declined; examples included higher abundance of Scotch argus adults and meadow neb moth caterpillars in some abandoned or uncut grasslands, and local extinctions of large blue and silver-studded blue in some abandoned meadows; heath fritillary abundance was similar around six years after abandonment but lower after >25 years, with no caterpillars [3957, 3956].",
