{
  "query": "What is the state of the evidence regarding the success of restoring habitats after mining and quarrying activities for butterfly and moth conservation?",
  "relevant_summary": "Four studies have evaluated restoring or creating habitats after mining and quarrying for butterflies and moths, conducted in the Czech Republic (two studies), the UK (one), and New Zealand (one) [3862]. A replicated, paired, site comparison study in the Czech Republic found technically restored quarries had lower species richness of butterflies and day\u2011flying moths than quarries left to restore naturally [3862]. Another replicated, paired, site comparison study in the Czech Republic found flattened spoil heaps had lower moth species richness than unflattened heaps, and 15% of 380 invertebrate species (including 208 moth species) were only found on flattened heaps compared to 30% only on unflattened heaps [3862]. A replicated, randomized, controlled study in the UK on slate waste tips found fertilizer application on trees did not change caterpillar abundance compared to unfertilized trees [3862]. A site comparison study in New Zealand found a peat bog restored after mining supported Fred the thread moth caterpillars with similar density and size to those in undisturbed bogs [3862].",
